<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1436,151,644]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
This species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bolton &amp; Fisher" authorityYear="2012" box="[571,606,405,428]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Simopone" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rex">
<emphasis box="[571,606,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">rex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sharing its relatively short frontal carinae and unarmed posterior corners of AII. However, the two have a consistently different shape to the anterior clypeal margin in front of the antennal sockets, and the vast majority of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bolton &amp; Fisher" authorityYear="2012" box="[520,584,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Simopone" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silens">
<emphasis box="[520,584,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">silens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens have very fine striolate sculpture on the propodeal declivity. The male of this species is known, see under Malagasy males, below.
</paragraph>
